AGI - Inaugurated, in Turin, in via degli Abeti 16, the Social Veterinary Office of the ASL City of Turin - free veterinary centre for the most fragile people - in the presence of the regional Councillor for animal welfare, Chiara Caucino, in addition to the leadership of the Piedmontese Health, the Asl City of Turin and other numerous exponents of the institutions and associations that deal with the care of animals. It is a flagship for Piedmont and, at the same time, a milestone in support of the most inconvenienced people for whom an animal of affection represents much more than a friend, but a true companion of life, a figure always present that gives love and affection, with proven therapeutic effects on mood and against the sense of loneliness> that often abounds in the most fragile people. To the Turin clinic, as well as to all of Piedmont, they will be able to access animals in charge of social services.
<br> Other 12 other centres have been activated: Alessandria, Asti, Arona, Biella, Borgosesia, Collegno, Cuneo, Moncalieri, two centers in Novara, Settimo Torinese and Verbania. In the coming weeks will be inaugurated the centers of Domodossola and Omegna, bringing the total number to 15>. All this has been made possible thanks to the will of the many who have worked to arrive to this extraordinary result, with the coordination of the allotted to Animal Welfare, to make team, firstly the Asl of the various territories and associations, besides of course to the Municipalities. The total expenditure, for the Region, amounts in fact altogether to 310 thousand euros>, sign that the resources are important, but even more important is the dedication and desire to do together something concrete for the most fragile and their four-legged friends. In order to be able to access the service the owner of the animal must report the need to the social services from which it is followed that they will arrange the appointment with the veterinarian of the Asl.(AGI)
&nbsp;
&nbsp;"The Piedmont is in the front row for animal welfare. This is demonstrated by this project that now arrives in Turin and which is a first step towards the mutual for animals for people in economic difficulty: It is scientifically proven that the company and the closeness of an animal of affection are important for people, especially for those more fragile - > declares the president of the Piedmont Region, Alberto Cirio - In this framework, last week, the Regional Council approved the law on animal welfare, an avant-garde measure in the Italian landscape, which regulates the care of animals of affection in the utmost respect of their well-being and their health. It foresees, among other things, the ban on the chain and the obligation to guarantee to animals spaces for mobility and race, regulates the criteria and places of burial of animals of affection and punishes abandonment and randagism".
&nbsp;
"It continues towards its conclusion - Caucino has explained - our path of inauguration of the 15 Piedmontese veterinary clinics, including that, very important, of the Asl City of Turin, the capital of our Piedmont.
&nbsp;
The situation, after the pandemic, of deep economic crisis, has heavily affected the fragile subjects in need followed by the Piedmontese social services that, in many cases, are holders of pets of affection". "For this reason - Caucino added - the objectives of this measure are multiple: avoid the abandonment of animals, perhaps because &nbsp; you do not have the resources to cure them, make sure that the most fragile people do not have to suffer a further economic aggression for the coming of a disease to their own animal and avoid that critical hygienic-sanitary situations can further worsen the situation of people already in difficulty".
<br> Caucino also thanked the League Anti Vivisezione (LAV) "for the great attention reserved to this initiative that has been realized with the donation, for Piedmont, of a contribution of 25 thousand euros, the provision of its precious volunteers and with the recognition of the importance of what we have given me, in Rome, an award within the contest 'AnimaLav'. Finally, I remember that in just two years it was really done for animal welfare, with numerous specific outreach bands aimed at municipalities and working in schools, with the involvement of about 1700 boys".
&nbsp;
"Ringrazio la Regione Piemonte - said Carlo Picco, general manager Asl city of Turin - for supporting the realization of the Social Veterinary Ambulatory. We have welcomed the initiative very favourably because it represents an instrument of prevention in the perspective of the concept of One Health, where human and animal health are closely related to each other and the environment surrounding it".

